@node Console Model
@section Console Model

The console implementation in @file{kernel/src/console.c} uses an internal
80x25 text-cell model regardless of whether the physical display is:

@itemize @bullet
@item VGA text memory at @code{0xB8000}, or
@item a Multiboot-provided RGB framebuffer.
@end itemize

The text-cell model stores:

@itemize @bullet
@item the character byte,
@item foreground and background attributes,
@item cursor position,
@item scroll-region state,
@item alternate-screen state, and
@item parser state for escape sequences.
@end itemize

When a framebuffer is present, the console renders characters by drawing the
built-in 8x16 bitmap font from @file{kernel/src/console_font.c}.

@node ANSI and Terminal Features
@section ANSI and Terminal Features

The console parser supports a practical subset of ANSI and DEC terminal
behavior:

@itemize @bullet
@item cursor movement,
@item screen and line clearing,
@item scrolling regions,
@item insertion and deletion of lines and characters,
@item SGR color, bold, and reverse-video state,
@item save and restore of cursor position,
@item cursor hide and show,
@item alternate-screen enter and leave through private mode 1049, and
@item DEC line-drawing graphics through shift-out and shift-in handling.
@end itemize

This is the reason ncurses-style applications work at all in VibeOS.

@node Serial Port Backend
@section Serial Port Backend

@findex serial_putc
@findex serial_pollc

Serial support is implemented in @file{kernel/src/serial.c} using COM1 at
@code{0x3F8}.  The initialization sequence programs the UART directly through
I/O ports.

The console mirrors output to serial unconditionally.  This has two useful
effects:

@itemize @bullet
@item kernel diagnostics survive even when graphical output is unavailable, and
@item QEMU's @code{-serial stdio} option becomes a reliable way to watch the
system boot and interact with it.
@end itemize

Serial input is also part of the generic input path.

@node Keyboard and Input Multiplexing
@section Keyboard and Input Multiplexing

@findex input_poll_char
@findex keyboard_poll_char

The generic input layer in @file{kernel/src/input.c} merges:

@itemize @bullet
@item serial input, and
@item polled PS/2 keyboard input from @file{kernel/src/keyboard.c}.
@end itemize

The keyboard path:

@itemize @bullet
@item tracks shift and control state,
@item handles the extended-scancode prefix,
@item translates scancodes through normal and shifted key maps, and
@item converts control combinations into ASCII control characters where that
makes sense.
@end itemize

The generic input layer then normalizes:

@itemize @bullet
@item @code{\n} to @code{\r}, and
@item serial DEL to backspace.
@end itemize

Keyboard-generated signal peek and poll hooks exist in the interface, but the
current keyboard implementation returns @code{KEYBOARD_COMBO_SIGNAL_NONE}; the
job-control signal generation used by the TTY layer is driven instead by the
characters read through the terminal path.

@node TTY and Framebuffer Devices
@section TTY and Framebuffer Devices

The console is exposed to userland through two kinds of special files.

The TTY paths are:

@table @file
@item /dev/tty
Primary terminal device.

@item /dev/console
Alias of the same terminal behavior.
@end table

The framebuffer path is:

@table @file
@item /dev/fb0
Framebuffer device, only present when a valid Multiboot framebuffer was
discovered.
@end table

TTY ioctls support:

@itemize @bullet
@item @code{TCGETS},
@item @code{TCSETS}, @code{TCSETSW}, and @code{TCSETSF},
@item @code{TIOCGPGRP} and @code{TIOCSPGRP},
@item @code{TIOCGWINSZ}, and
@item @code{FIONREAD}.
@end itemize

Framebuffer ioctls support:

@itemize @bullet
@item @code{FBIOGET_FSCREENINFO},
@item @code{FBIOGET_VSCREENINFO},
@item @code{FBIOGETCMAP} and @code{FBIOPUTCMAP},
@item constrained @code{FBIOPUT_VSCREENINFO},
@item constrained @code{FBIOPAN_DISPLAY}, and
@item @code{FBIOBLANK}.
@end itemize

The framebuffer file also supports open, read, write, and seek operations by
directly accessing the mapped physical framebuffer range.

@node Power Management and Reset
@section Power Management and Reset

@findex power_init
@findex power_reboot

Power management is implemented in @file{kernel/src/power.c}.  The kernel:

@enumerate
@item locates RSDP information through Multiboot tags,
@item prefers the ACPI 2.0+ XSDT path when available,
@item falls back to the RSDT path when needed,
@item locates the FADT,
@item locates the DSDT, and
@item parses AML just far enough to recover the S5 sleep-type values.
@end enumerate

Shutdown first attempts ACPI S5 through the PM1 control registers.  If that
does not work, the kernel tries several emulator-friendly fallback ports and
then halts.

Reboot uses the keyboard controller reset command.  Halt simply disables
interrupts and loops on @code{hlt}.
